      <p><p>@alina Do you really not get that with things like this going on Roma are not exactly invited to turn in lost children to the 'proper authorities' or to try and go for legal adoption in the normal way? Around the time Maria ended up at Farsala, talk about Roma children in state institutions being sold for organ harvesting was all over the place! No wonder they just kept her without ringing bells. No, in other countries babies are not sold and everyone happy with it, because 'private' adoptions for cash from state institutions also does not take place, because private adoption is illegal for all, Roma, non-Roma and the state! People don't seem to realise what the often-used term of 'scapegoating' actually means anymore. But if I read 100+ comments of people saying: Well the Greek state is right to take Maria away as we know there is children trafficking INVOLVING the Roma community....yes, involving. But involving how? As victims, that is . The accusation of selling, trafficking, exploiting are actively kept in the sphere of the Roma and this poor couple, not where it belongs: With doctors, lawyers, agencies....</p></p>
