  <section class="fyre-comment-body">
    <div class="fyre-comment">
      <p><p>Your intuitions have proven correct, it seems.  I'm amazed by this story.  My mother traveled 2000 miles from Providence, R I, where she lived, to Memphis, Tennessee where my father was stationed in the U S Air Force in order catch up with him after she became pregnant with his child - me.  They married quickly just three months before I was born, three days before Christmas in 1951.  She was dark haired and dark eyed with an Italian name.  I learned later in life that my father's family, the parents of which - my grandparents - were both Irish immigrants,  was suspicious and prejudiced towards her.  Of the  seven children of my father's family, four were bright red heads,  the other three, strawberry blonds.   I often wonder how circumstances might have been mitigated  after I came out of her womb with bright red hair.  People have a racist and sexist (mis) understanding of genetics.  We're not barnyard animals.  It's time to stop treating people as if they are. </p></p>
    </div>
    
  </section>

